<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-038-217 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 434 491</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 7 1991 v25 n40 p102(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Costs are declining for TCP/IP on PC LANs. (includes relatedarticle on estimated cost of putting Transmission ControlProtocol/Internet Protocol on local area networks) (ProductSpotlight)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smalley, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>It is becoming less costly to use Transmission ControlProtocol/Internet Protocol (TCP/IP) with microcomputer-based localarea networks because of development of TCP/IP software products.andO;The price of software is much lower, and the amount of memory usedby software has dropped so that DOS machines no longer need memoryboosts to run TCP/IP.andP;  More funds are saved by utilizing theNetwork Device Interface because the standard enables multipleprotocol support to be cost effective.andP;  Further cost savings canbe realized in the area of training and support because more andmore software vendors are using Microsoft Corp's popular MicrosoftWindows 3.0 graphical user interface with their TCP/IP softwarepackages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol (Computer networkprotocol)ProtocolMicrocomputersCost ReductionSoftware PackagesComputer industryLocal area networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>